{"key":"post-8901371","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8901371</id>\n<content>It's not so much misinformation as updated technique.&amp;nbsp; If you make your cakes a tad on the dry side, they'll colonize much faster and be more bacteria resistant.&amp;nbsp; However, dry cakes don't fruit well.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;My suggestion is to use the standard 1-1-2 ratio for your pf cakes, but use fine verm instead of course.&amp;nbsp; Fine verm holds more water per cup of verm, therefore your cakes will be drier and colonize faster.&amp;nbsp; At full colonization, wait one week for the mycelium to &lt;i&gt;consolidate&lt;/i&gt; it's hold on the substrate, then birth the cakes, and dunk and roll to provide the extra moisture to support a flush.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Disregard posts about not letting your cakes get wet in the terrarium.&amp;nbsp; The old pf style terrarium was completely sealed up, and even had a drip shield to prevent water droplets from the lid landing on the cakes.&amp;nbsp; It had to be fanned out several times per day.&amp;nbsp; That was fine in the 90's, but we've developed better ways of doing it since that time.&amp;nbsp; We now know that constant air exchange is better than letting the air get stale and then fanning it out a few times a day.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;There's several ways of doing this, but I feel the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium tek&lt;/a&gt; is the easiest way for new folks to get started, especially when you have to work 8 or more hours per day and you're not around to fan out your terrarium. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, with the shotgun terrarium, don't worry about getting your cakes wet when you mist.&amp;nbsp; You're supposed to.&amp;nbsp; Evaporation of moisture from a substrate is one of the top pinning triggers.&amp;nbsp; Therefore, you need to get your cakes wet at misting in order to make up for the lost moisture.&amp;nbsp; With all those holes in the terrarium, they'll naturally dry out a bit between mistings, and then you replace that moisture.&amp;nbsp; Good luck.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>8901298</prev>\n<first>8901087</first>\n<last>8901371</last>\n<when>1220977820</when>\n<utime>09/09/08 07:30 PM</utime>\n</post>"}